value.value: A dietary supplement containing calcium lactate, protease, amylase and lipase, that may be used as a calcium supplement and for the prevention and treatment of osteoporosis, and to decrease inflammation and improve tissue repair. Upon administration of calcium lactate/protease/amylase/lipase-containing supplement, the enzymes catalyze the breakdown of fats, carbohydrates and proteins during the digestion of food. This increases the absorption of amino acids, which may decrease inflammation and improve tissue repair. Calcium lactate helps maintain calcium balance and prevent bone loss. Calcium is a major component of bone and teeth that confers bone strength and structure, and plays an important role in many physiologic functions including nerve, muscle and cardiac functions.

label.value: Cerebellar Ataxia, Neuropathy, and Vestibular Areflexia Syndrome

value.value: A rare autosomal recessive condition caused by mutation(s) in the RFC1 gene, encoding replication factor C subunit 1. It is characterized by cerebellar dysfunction, bilateral vestibulopathy, and axonal neuropathy.
A genetic condition associated with mutation(s) in the ADCY5 gene, encoding adenylate cyclase 5. It is characterized by abnormal involuntary movements with orofacial involvement.

Specific molecular molecules or signatures that indicate that a cell will become neoplastic at a future time.
A significant condition that is neither the immediate, intervening, originating, nor underlying cause of death but which contributed to the fatal outcome.
A rare cyst that results from traumatic (usually surgical) implantation of respiratory epithelium in the jaw bones.

label.value: Clear Cell Calcifying Epithelial Odontogenic Tumor

value.value: A calcifying epithelial odontogenic tumor that contains a variable proportion of clear cells containing diastase-labile PAS-positive material that is consistent with glycogen.
A calcifying epithelial odontogenic tumor characterized by cystic/microcystic changes.

label.value: Non-Calcifying/Langerhans Cell-Rich Calcifying Epithelial Odontogenic Tumor

value.value: A calcifying epithelial odontogenic tumor that contains significant numbers of Langerhans cells.
A technique that uses dyes and/or radioactive agents to map the lymphatic drainage of an area in which a tumor is located, thereby identifying the sentinel node.
An indication that ACTA2 expression has been detected in a sample.
A rare ameloblastoma characterized by the presence of cribriform architecture and the formation of duct-like structures. Dentinoid is usually present.
A regimen containing fruquintinib that can be used in the treatment of colorectal cancer (CRC) and appendiceal adenocarcinoma.
Any agent that inhibits the activity of porcupine (PORCN).
Any agent that inhibits the Wnt signaling pathway.
This gene is involved in enamel formation and odontogenesis.

Human AMBN wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 4q13.3 and is approximately 15 kb in length. This allele, which encodes ameloblastin protein, plays a role in tooth enamel mineralization and matrix formation. Mutation of the gene is associated with amelogenesis imperfecta 1F.
Ameloblastin (447 aa, ~48 kDa) is encoded by the human AMBN gene. This protein is involved in the mineralization and structure of tooth enamel.
A milk product made by lactic acid fermentation or a combination of this and yeast fermentation.

label.value: Intellectual Developmental Disorder, X-Linked, Syndromic, Nascimento Type

value.value: An X-linked recessive condition caused by mutation(s) in the UBE2A gene, encoding ubiquitin-conjugating enzyme E2 A. It is characterized by facial dysmorphisms and intellectual impairment.

Non-homologous DNA end joining (NHEJ) can only repair double-strand breaks in which two DNA ends are rejoined by DNA ligase at regions of little or no homology to avoid degradation by DNA nucleases or noncomplementary overhanging ends. However, the disadvantage is that it can lead to loss of information from the DNA because of resection of the broken ends. NHEJ is operational throughout the cell cycle but may be more important during G1, prior to DNA replication, or in cells that are no longer cycling.

An autosomal dominant condition caused by mutation in the C1QTNF5 gene, encoding complement C1q tumor necrosis factor-related protein 5. It is characterized by dark adaptation abnormalities, sub-retinal pigment epithelium lipid-rich material deposits, choroidal neovascularization, and chorioretinal atrophy. The typical onset is in the fifth or sixth decade of life.
A condition in which the ligamentum flavum is progressively ossified which may cause compression of elements inside the spinal canal, resulting in various neurological symptoms.

A genetically heterogenous condition characterized by round, nodular masses of normal neurons and glial cells with no laminar organization near the ventricles. Patients often develop drug-resistant epilepsy.

An autosomal recessive condition caused by mutation(s) in the PLA2G6 gene, encoding 85/88 kDa calcium-independent phospholipase A2. It is characterized by axonal swelling and spheroid bodies in the central nervous system. The onset is typically in the first two years of life.
Universal health care coverage provided by any of Canada's 13 provinces to their citizens.

An endoscopic surgical procedure designed to give transanal access to resecting benign, premalignant, or early malignant lesions in the mid- to proximal rectum. Transanal endoscopic microsurgery (TEM) and transanal endoscopic operation (TEO) are rigid platforms, whereas transanal minimally invasive surgery (TAMIS) is a flexible platform.

A metabolic disorder caused by polymorphisms in the LPA gene that affect the number of kringle-4 repeats in the encoded protein, apolipoprotein(a) (apo(a)). The number of kringle-4 repeats are inversely correlated with apo(a) expression in the blood. Thus, forms of apo(a) with fewer repeats are expressed at elevated levels, which leads to increased concentrations of apo(a)-containing lipoprotein particles and an elevated risk for atherosclerosis, cardiovascular disease, and coronary artery disease.
An odontogenic fibroma that arises from tooth-forming tissues in the mandible and maxilla.
A central odontogenic fibroma characterized by the presence of amyloid deposits. Langerhans cells are often present in the odontogenic epithelium.
A central odontogenic fibroma composed of granular cells admixed with odontogenic epithelium.
This gene plays a role in telomerase activity.
A central odontogenic fibroma characterized by the presence of odontogenic fibroma components admixed with ossifying fibroma-like tissue.

label.value: Hybrid Odontogenic Fibroma with Central Giant Cell Granuloma

value.value: A central odontogenic fibroma characterized by the presence of combined histological features of giant cell granuloma and odontogenic fibroma.
A response to treatment that approaches a complete clinical response but does not meet all criteria.
Lack of a clinical response to treatment.
A ten question measure designed to assess swallowing difficulties.
A question about whether an individual has or had weight loss due to swallowing problems.

label.value: Swallowing Problem Interferes with Ability to Go Out for Meals

value.value: A question about whether an individual's swallowing problems interferes or interfered with their ability to go out for meals.
A question about whether an individual's swallowing of liquid takes extra effort.
A question about whether an individual's swallowing of solids takes extra effort.
A question about whether an individual's swallowing of pills takes extra effort.
Epithelial cell adhesion molecule (314 aa, ~35 kDa) is encoded by the human EPCAM gene. This protein is involved in both cell adhesion and cellular proliferation.
